{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17473557","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17473557"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:10:47+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:10:47+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2519"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2519","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2519"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.23,0.26,0.22,0.27]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2519"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101933"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2519","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2519"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2519"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84390"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"17"},{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"37"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"305"},{"type":"tags","id":"1571"},{"type":"tags","id":"4088"},{"type":"tags","id":"4111"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4983"},{"type":"tags","id":"4985"},{"type":"tags","id":"4989"},{"type":"tags","id":"4990"},{"type":"tags","id":"5631"},{"type":"tags","id":"5671"},{"type":"tags","id":"5686"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"11643"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2381"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2406"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3245"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35210"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35211"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43173"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44842"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101933","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/101933"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 16-year-old girl presents alone to the General Practice clinic requesting contraception. She lives in Victoria. She reports painful heavy periods since menarche at age 11, with simple analgesia being ineffective in managing her symptoms. She has been sexually active since age 13 years, and also mentions having a white vaginal discharge with discomfort for the past three weeks. She uses condoms occasionally but predominately relies on the \u0027pull out\u0027 method.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EShe has researched contraceptive options extensively and understands the potential risks, benefits, and costs of various methods. She does not want her parents to know about her seeking contraception as they do not know she is sexually active and they are very religious. During the consultation, she mentions that her mother had an unprovoked deep vein thrombosis. She does not have any significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EShe is articulate and demonstrates good understanding of the information discussed during the consultation.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate course of action?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Delay prescription until discussion with parents as she is a minor with health risks","Prescribe the oral combined contraceptive pill","Inserting an etonogestrel implant","Referring to adolescent gynaecology services","Inserting a levonorgestrel intrauterine system"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis question addresses issues of informed consent, Gillick competence, and appropriate contraceptive choices for adolescents with specific clinical considerations. The girl demonstrates characteristics of Gillick competence - she has researched contraceptive options, understands the implications, and can articulate her needs. She also has a family history of thrombosis and symptoms suggesting possible sexually transmitted infection (chlamydia with vaginal discharge and discomfort).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInserting an etonogestrel implant\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate option. The implant is a highly effective long-acting reversible contraceptive that is not contraindicated by her family history of thrombosis. Before insertion, appropriate testing for sexually transmitted infections should be performed given her symptoms of vaginal discharge though it is not a contraindication for insertion. In certain causes, alternative locations such as the upper thigh to prevent detection from other people can be considered however has the risk of being inserted too deep or migrating.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDelay prescription until discussion with parents as she is a minor with health risks\u003C/strong\u003E violates the girl\u0027s confidentiality and autonomy as she has been assessed as Gillick competent. At 16 years of age in Victoria, she is legally able to consent to her own medical treatment. Forcing parental involvement against her wishes could lead to her avoiding healthcare altogether, potentially resulting in an unintended pregnancy or untreated infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrescribe the oral combined contraceptive pill\u003C/strong\u003E would be contraindicated given her mother\u0027s history of unprovoked deep vein thrombosis, which suggests a possible inherited thrombophilia or at very least, requires further information from the parent. Combined hormonal contraceptives increase the risk of thrombosis, and this risk is higher in those with a family history of unprovoked thrombosis. Even progestogen-only pills, while safer regarding thrombosis risk, have lower effectiveness with typical use compared to long-acting reversible contraceptives.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReferring to adolescent gynaecology services\u003C/strong\u003E is unnecessary in this case as a general practitioner can appropriately assess Gillick competence and provide contraception. This would delay care and potentially increase the risk of unintended pregnancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInserting a levonorgestrel intrauterine system\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate before ruling out chlamydia or other infections, given her symptoms of white discharge and discomfort. Insertion of an intrauterine device in the presence of untreated sexually transmitted infections increases the risk of pelvic inflammatory disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn Victoria, a 16-year-old is considered capable of consenting to their own medical treatment. Under the Gillick competency principle, even younger adolescents can consent to medical treatment if they are deemed to have sufficient maturity and intelligence to understand the treatment and its implications. The patient has demonstrated this understanding, and her request for confidentiality should be respected while ensuring appropriate medical care is provided.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Gillick competence allows minors under 16 to consent to medical treatment if they demonstrate sufficient maturity and understanding of the treatment and its implications.","When prescribing contraception to adolescents, both confidentiality and safety must be balanced appropriately.","Family history of thrombosis is a contraindication to combined hormonal contraceptives."],"references":["Griffith R. What is Gillick competence. Hum Vaccine Immunother. 2016; 12(1): 244-247.","Bird S. Consent to medical treatment: the mature minor. Medicus. 2011 Oct;51(9):54-55.","Ross S, Polyakov A. Contraception options during pubertal transitions: risks, benefits and considerations.  Australian Journal of General Practice. 2024: 53 (10).  Available at: https://www1.racgp.org.au/ajgp/2024/october/contraception-options-during-pubertal-transition"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84390"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2519"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84390","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/84390"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-05T16:52:45+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-05T16:52:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2519"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101933"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"17","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/17"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude07","name":"Bioethics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":nul